This case involves a 03-months old female patient received a dose from a vial of IPV (VERO) [IPOL] which was the 11th dose from a vial which contained 10 doses. the 11th dose was a full 0.5 ml (incorrect dose administered) (batch number: R1B251M and expiration date: unknown) via unknown route and unknown site for prophylactic vaccination.  Medical history, medical treatment(s), vaccination(s) and family history were not provided.  Concomitant medications included HIB VACCINE CONJ (TET TOX) (ACTHIB), DIPHTHERIA VACCINE TOXOID, PERTUSSIS VACCINE ACELLULAR, TETANUS VACCINE TOXOID (DAPTACEL), LABETALOL HYDROCHLORIDE (IPOLAB) and PNEUMOCOCCAL VACCINE CONJ 13V (CRM197) (PREVNAR 13).  It was an actual medication error due to the inappropriate dose of drug administered (latency: unknown).  At the time of reporting, the patient had no adverse event.  Disclaimer: This suspected adverse reaction report is submitted and classified as a medication error solely and exclusively to ensure the marketing authorization holder's compliance with the requirements set out in Directive 2001/83/EC and Module VI of the Good Pharmacovigilance Practices. The classification as a medical error is in no way intended, nor should it be interpreted or construed as an allegation or claim made by the marketing authorization holder that any third party has contributed to or is to be held liable for the occurrence of this medication error.

I then started feeling very nauseous, but I was shaking so badly that I had to very carefully  hold the toilet  to turn around to kneel down in front of the toilet. I heaved a number of times, but nothing came up. I finally stopped shaking and sat on the floor in front of the toilet for a while, and the sweating got less. After a short time, I got up and walked slowly to a recliner, about 30' away. The nausea had gone away by then and the sweating had subsided. My wife brought me blanket and I rested till 7:30 AM. SYMPTOM_TEXT: I received dose 1 of Pfizer COVID-19 vaccine on Feb 24.  The initial symptoms starting Feb 25 were somnolence, mild muscle stiffness and dizziness that lasted approx 5-6 days but gradually resolved.  Approx 3 days after the shot I developed chills, which took approx 2 weeks to resolve.  As for neurologic symptoms, approx 6 days after the shot, I experienced a worsening of my peripheral neuropathy that is still ongoing >2 weeks since dose 1 (normally very mild at baseline and mostly limited to the feet).  This exacerbation manifested primarily as stockings/gloves sensation to the mid-calves and elbows/mid-upper arms. I have also experienced some tingling in hand/feet and a notable cold sensation in the feet (worst in the toes- when I step into hot water in the shower, the feet/toes become quite painful and a transient blotchy redness appears on the feet).  The stockings/gloves sensation and foot coldness persist though approx 50% better than when it started.  No muscle weakness or myalgias accompany these symptoms.  I am concerned about receiving my 2nd dose on March 26 given the ongoing presence of symptoms from the first.  I have scheduled an appt to discuss with my Rheumatologist. My Neurologist is unsure I should receive 2nd dose.

Pt. had no symptoms the following Wednesday (3/10/21). SYMPTOM_TEXT: ?I recd the first moderna vaccine 2-13-2021 at 11 AM.  Headache, right side only, started same day at 7:30 PM, sore shoulder at vaccine site about 10:30 PM same day.  Both were gone the next morning.  I recd the second dose of the moderna vaccine 3-13-2021 at 11 AM.  By 2 PM I had a ranging head ache, again right side only.  I drove four hours to the vaccination site, hospital.  I was driving home when this started.  I stopped to purchase Tylenol about 3 pm which it turns out had no effect.  I was driving west into a setting sun, as the headache got worse, my eyes became more and more sensitive to the sun, I stopped a second time to purchase a second pair of sunglasses that I could wear over the first pair, that didn?t help, I ended up stopping at a rest area until the sun set.  I got to my house at about 6 PM, by then I could no longer wear my prescription glasses, besides the headache I was now very dizzy.  At about 9 PM the pain started, between my shoulder blades first, never at the injection site.  From that time on, including today, the pain has constantly moved around my body, the worst pain is associated with areas that arthritis affects me, hips, knees, hands, ankles.  I have had a mild fever, ranging from 100.9 Saturday night to 100.3 now at11 AM 3-15-2021.  Yesterday, 3-14, my head was swearing, my feet were ice cold.  I had an electric blanket from my waist down and an ice pack on head.  If I have ever felt worse in my life I don?t remember when that would have been.  The pain has moderated today, I expect the worst is now over.    If as the health specialists are suggesting a booster will be required this fall I will undoubtedly have incredibly significant reservations with this vaccine.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: On Monday evening, I started feeling rather weird, rather out of it. During the night, I was having trouble sleeping and woke up with a fever of 100. I took Tylenol and went back to bed.  When I finally got up probably around 10 a.m., I was not feeling well at all.  I had body aches, a headache, stomach cramps, chills, fever, my arm was very sore, very tired, and exhausted. I fell back asleep early afternoon and woke up with a 101.7 fever. Took Tylenol & continued to not feel well.  Went to bed around 10 p.m. and slept for 12 hours.  Wednesday, I was still very exhausted, but not as many body aches. That evening, I noticed my face had many small pimples on it.  The next morning, I woke up with a rash and redness around the injection area, a rash on my face and on other areas of my body, which caused itching/tingling sensations.  I called the health department nurse and she indicated that the rash was also a side effect of the vaccine.  She suggested Benadryl, but I mentioned that I don't handle that medication very well.  I did use some Benadryl cream on my arm for the itching.  Not sure whether the cream caused a reaction, but I once again became very tired and took a nap.  I also developed a stuffed, clogged left ear, which affected my hearing.  This sensation came and went several times from Thursday through Sunday. On Friday, I still had a rash and experienced some fatigue.  When I woke up on Saturday, I finally felt like I was "normal" again.

To give context to the adverse event, in early November 2020 I was diagnosed with Bell's Palsy of unknown origin on the left side of my face. I was tested for COVID-19 and it came back negative. It resolved itself in about a month. About 8 hours after receiving the COVID-19 vaccine on 3/9/21 (about 6:30 p.m., I started to feel a slight headache. Because I had just had the vaccine, I was trying to avoid taking any pain medication, so I did not take anything for it. The headache got worse throughout the evening, and by 10 p.m. I would describe it as a moderate headache. It was primarily concentrated on the left side of my head towards the front, on my forehead and above the eyebrow. I went to bed without taking any pain medication. About 3 hours later, at about 1 p.m., I woke up, and the headache was much more intense. It felt like all the nerves around the left side of my face, including the nerve along my jaw line leading to the 7th cranial nerve that causes Bell's Palsy, were throbbing. I grew concerned about getting Bell's Palsy again, so at that time I took one ibuprofen Advil. After taking it, the headache subsided, although I continued to have a dull headache throughout the night and the next day.
ALLERGIES: Allergic to penicillin (anaphylaxis at age 7), sulpha (rash), aspirin (possible)

3/6/21  This is a 32-year-old female who is receiving her first Johnson & Johnson Covid vaccine and shortly afterwards developed some throat itching and tightness.  She was given a milligram of epinephrine by intramuscular injection by retired emergency physician there and then transported by ambulance here for further evaluation.  Says her tongue felt a little swollen as well but she denies any respiratory symptoms.  Her voice sounds crackly to her.  She denies any pruritus or rashes.  She has had multiple allergic reactions to medications in the past but never having to be admitted overnight.  One episode however did occur while she was hospitalized and receiving treatment.  She has never had to be intubated.  She has had isolated urticaria without oral or throat symptoms and vice versa.  At this point she says she does feel somewhat better. She is given IV dexamethasone and observed here.  At 1 point she complained of it complaint complained of it feeling like a tightening in the back of her throat was worsening.  She is given an additional intramuscular dose of epinephrine with epinephrine and on reexamination had no significant change in physical findings or her phonation.  This occurred again and she was given viscous lidocaine with minimal improvement in her symptoms.  After several hours of observation without objective worsening but continued complaint of feeling increasing tightness in her throat, CT imaging of the neck is performed to assess the soft tissue structures.  No abnormalities or indication of significant retropharyngeal or paralaryngeal edema or airway compromise present. Given the possibility of some laryngeal muscle or parapharyngeal muscle spasm as him, she was given Flexeril.  After some discussion with her I did indicate to her that I felt it would be safe to return home but offered admission for observation as well.  She indicated she was comfortable returning home for continued observation.  She will be continued on steroids and antihistamines and is given additional Flexeril by prescription if this does seem to help her symptoms.  If no improvement over the next 2 to 3 days and follow-up either with her primary providers through facility or Dr.  3/7/21: Return to ED. The patient is in no respiratory distress.  She has no wheezing.  On physical exam her throat lips and tongue look fine.  I think she is not a had another allergic reaction, rebounded from yesterday.  She is not on any type of steroids sinus syndrome with some Decadron.  And she is allergic to Benadryl but she can take Claritin if she wants.  Her CBC and chemistry were normal.  I went back to evaluate her and she still getting fluids and now she is complaining of shooting pain down her left leg from the EpiPen.  Again she has this regional complex pain syndrome that could be part of that but there is nothing I can do for this at this time.  In terms of her allergic reaction she feels much better her throat feels normal.  We will send her out with prescription for Decadron and EpiPen and if she gets worse she will come back and will follow up admit her.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: To give context to the adverse event, in early November 2020 I was diagnosed with Bell's Palsy of unknown origin on the left side of my face. I was tested for COVID-19 and it came back negative. It resolved itself in about a month. About 8 hours after receiving the COVID-19 vaccine on 3/9/21 (about 6:30 p.m., I started to feel a slight headache. Because I had just had the vaccine, I was trying to avoid taking any pain medication, so I did not take anything for it. The headache got worse throughout the evening, and by 10 p.m. I would describe it as a moderate headache. It was primarily concentrated on the left side of my head towards the front, on my forehead and above the eyebrow. I went to bed without taking any pain medication. About 3 hours later, at about 1 p.m., I woke up, and the headache was much more intense. It felt like all the nerves around the left side of my face, including the nerve along my jaw line leading to the 7th cranial nerve that causes Bell's Palsy, were throbbing. I grew concerned about getting Bell's Palsy again, so at that time I took one ibuprofen Advil. After taking it, the headache subsided, although I continued to have a dull headache throughout the night and the next day. Patient received the vaccine Monday March 1st around 2:30pm. Patient began to feel arm soreness around 5pm, woke up at 3am the following morning with a severe headache and spent the next day resting. Wednesday morning March 3rd, the patient reported extreme fatigue, dizziness and feeling "woozy". As she was walking around the store, around 8:30am, patient had to request help as she almost fainted. Patient went home quickly after, reported dizziness until 3pm. Patient's friend who is a nurse came to her home to check her vitals, confirmed they were normal and encouraged fluids/rest. After resting further Wednesday/Thursday, patient returned to work Friday morning and has been fine since. Patient did not take any medications prior/during/after incident.
LAB_DATA: Vitals checked by friend (nurse) Wednesday March 3rd
OTHER_MEDS: Multivitamin, biotin, Calcium, Vitamin c, Vitamin E, fish oil

Patient received Janssen vaccine by registered nurse and was completing her 15 minute waiting period. She began to feel faint and an employee of our facility caught her as she experienced a near syncopal episode. She was promptly placed in Trendelenburg position and vitals obtained. BP was 90/58 with mild tachycardia to max of 130-140 bpm. Patient was given supportive treatment and monitored. BP improved to 110/70 after 5 minutes and 120/72 after 15 minutes. Patient continued to feel very dizzy and weak, however, and became tachycardic and diaphoretic each time she attempted to move to a seated position. Eventually the chills turned into a fever and my body temperature suddenly shot up. I didn't have a thermometer, but it was certainly over 100 degrees Fahrenheit. Despite my relief from the chills, I still couldn't sleep.  I wasn't remarkably stressed/anxious, I just couldn't get to sleep. I'm not typically an insomniac, and upon speaking to others who received the same vaccine, they've also reported intense chills and an inability to fall asleep.

These include her getting up at night and sundowning as well as yelling and screaming during the day.  Daughter states that she gets in the shouting matches with the patient during the day.  Daughter breaks down and starts to cry when discussing that she thinks her mother will need long-term placement as she is having a difficult time dealing with her behaviors. Unfortunately, patient's overall function declined after, and she was refusing/unable to eat or drink. She was transitioned to comfort care status on 03/03/2021. Case client was in attendance at Vaccine clinic on 3/3/2021.  After receiving the vaccine the client went into the monitoring area staffed by local EMTs.  She verbalized that she was having nausea and dizziness in waves, the EMTs gave her some juice and crackers, which did not resolve the issue.  Client verbalized that while being monitored her blood pressure was taken and was 200/100.  She denies any past/current health issues, takes no medication and has NKDA.  She was never had a reaction to vaccines in the past.  Client verbalized the feelings of nausea and dizziness occurred within 5 -10 minutes of receiving the vaccine.  She was transported via squad to the local hospital due to her blood pressure continued to rise.  During transport she reports a BP of 224/120.  Case client was monitored in the ED for approximately 2-3 hours and reports was given no medications or fluids, just monitored.  Her BP returned to a level that the hospital felt comfortable releasing her to go home.  This PHN followed up with the client the next day - on 3/4/2021 case client verbalized she went ahead and took the day off of work to rest, only complaint was a sore arm.  Nausea and dizziness has resolved, and denies any headache or chest discomfort. PHN encouraged client to go to her follow up appointment with doctor as scheduled and they should discuss together the risks and benefits of  receiving 2nd dose of the COVID Vaccine.  Case client verbalized understanding and declined any questions or concerns.  Case client received Moderna COVID19 Vaccine Lot #30A21A.
LAB_DATA: No additional testing was completed at ED visit.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The day I received the shot, my arm got warm and sore.  The soreness traveled to my shoulder and neck.  I got headachey, alternating between hot and cold chills, a little bit of nausea and extreme tiredness.   This continued for the next 5 days which seemed like they were considered mild reactions according to the CDC website.  Most concerning though, is on day 5, (3/14/21) in the evening as I was getting into bed, I started getting a red, extremely itchy rash on both my arms, my lower back and my upper legs, to the point that I could not sleep because it was so itchy and had to take Benedryl.  I have not changed anything in my diet or in the products I use on my body, so I can only attribute this reaction to this vaccine.  I am still a little itchy on my arms today 3/15/21.   I am also still getting the hot and cold chills and still have a little bit of nausea, not bad, but enough to be "off" certain foods.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Pt has called office to report reaction after vaccination. Pt. reports that approximately 30 minutes after vaccination (she was already home), she became very itchy, all over. She then noted her lips were numb. Her throat was itchy and then felt to be swelling. She did not have trouble breathing, but did feel it was difficult to swallow. Pt did take benadryl which helped lessen the reaction. After the benadryl wore off, the symptoms would return. She took the benadryl every 6 hrs for 24 hours per patient until symptoms resolved. She did also develop flu-like symptoms the evening of the vaccine, which persist still 3/15/21. She did not go to the ER or to see a doctor through this. Patient questioning taking second vaccine - advised to speak with her PCP.  After speaking with PCP, patient is opting out of second vaccine.

had autoimmune anemia / hemoglobin was lower than 8 / Hematocrit was 9.3; physical rash over her entire body; fever of 103; was sick; low hematocrit; first dose of Shingrix in June 2019.  She never received the second dose; low hemoglobin; night sweats; hives with heat; hives with heat; This case was reported by a consumer via call center representative and described the occurrence of autoimmune anemia in a 70-year-old female patient who received Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Co-suspect products included paracetamol (Tylenol) for rash and Herpes zoster (Shingrix) for prophylaxis.   Concurrent medical conditions included hashimoto's disease.   In June 2019, the patient received the 1st dose of Shingrix (intramuscular). On an unknown date, the patient started Tylenol at an unknown dose and frequency and the 2nd dose of Shingrix. On an unknown date, less than 6 months after receiving Shingrix and not applicable after receiving Shingrix, the patient experienced autoimmune anemia (serious criteria GSK medically significant), night sweats, feeling hot, hives, rash, fever, sickness, hemoglobin decreased, hematocrit decreased and incomplete course of vaccination. The action taken with Tylenol was unknown. In November 2019, the outcome of the hematocrit decreased was recovered/resolved. On an unknown date, the outcome of the autoimmune anemia, night sweats, feeling hot, hives, rash, fever, sickness and hemoglobin decreased were recovered/resolved and the outcome of the incomplete course of vaccination was unknown.   It was unknown if the reporter considered the autoimmune anemia, night sweats, feeling hot, hives, rash, fever, sickness, hemoglobin decreased and hematocrit decreased to be related to Shingrix.  Additional information was provided as follows: The age at vaccination was not reported, however could be 69 or 70 years. The patient received 2nd dose of vaccine in her right arm. The patient never received the second dose due to the side effects she experienced, which led to incomplete course of vaccination. The patient was sick, had a fever of 103 for more than one week. She had a physical rash over her entire body and she took Tylenol. She had hives with heat that lasted for 8 days. She had night sweats for 2 weeks. Her doctor drew blood and it was determined with hemoglobin that she had autoimmune anemia. Her hemoglobin was lower than 8 which resolved after 6 months. Her Hematocrit was 9.3 which resolved in late November 2019.  The patient was unsure if the physical rash she experienced was related to the Shingrix or the Tylenol.  All of the patient's side effects had resolved till the time of reporting. It was unknown if the reporter considered the Tylenol to be related to reported events. The reporter consented to follow up

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Meniere's attack; Anaphylactic reaction; Started passing out; doesn't feel well; Tired; light headed; A spontaneous report was received from a Consumer concerning a 85 years-old, female patient who received Moderna's COVID-19 vaccine (mRNA-1273) and experienced anaphylactic reaction (anaphylactic reaction), started passing out (loss of consciousness), Meniere's attack (Meniere's disease), tired (fatigue), light headed (dizziness) and doesn't feel well (malaise).   The patient's medical history included allergies to citrus and bee stings. Concomitant product use was not provided by the reporter.  On 15 FEB 2021, immediately prior to the onset of the symptoms, the patient received their first of two planned doses of mRNA-1273 (Lot number: 031L20A) via unknown route in the left arm for prophylaxis of COVID-19 infection.  On 15 FEB 2021, immediately post vaccination, the patient got an anaphylactic reaction and started passing. The patient was transported to the emergency room where medication was administered and an echocardiogram (ECG) was performed (results not provided).  On 17 FEB 2021, the patient contacted physician who instructed to take Tylenol three times a day and nausea medication as needed. The patient only took one pill.  On 21 FEB 2021, the patient had a terrible Meniere's attack which caused patient to feel dizzy and was hospitalized. On an unknown date in FEB 2021, the patient returned home but couldn't get over it. Patient reported feeling very tired, lightheaded and unwell.  Treatment information included famotidine, Ativan, Zofran, Tylenol and nausea medication.  Action taken with mRNA-1273 in response to the events was unknown.  The events Meniere's attack, tired, lightheaded and doesn't feel well were considered not resolved. The event started passing out was considered resolved on 15 FEB 2021. The outcome of the event anaphylactic reaction was unknown.; Reporter's Comments: Based on the current available information and temporal association between the use of the product and the start date of the events, a causal relationship cannot be excluded.
CUR_ILL: Allergy to insect sting; Fruit allergy (Citrus)

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Admitted to hospital 3/13 with encephalopathy for monitoring.  Discharged 3/14.  At the beginning of ED visit, Patient did not know her daughter's name. She was unable to lift her legs at home when daughter tried to help patient to dress. At ED patient was given Tylenol and fluid. Patient now recognizes her daughter and was able to get up to the bathroom with only minor assistance. During encounter, patient is awake and able to follow directions. Patient is not oriented to time, though she know she is in the hospital. Patient states that she had COVID this morning and that is the reason why she was in the hospital. Daughter at bedside helped history. Patient received 2nd Moderna COVID 19 vaccination yesterday. Daughter called but patient did not respond at noon. daughter went over to see the patient. Patient could not finish the sentence to questions. Patient could not get her dressed up by herself. Patient went to bathroom for urination but she wiped the toilet, and folded the towel. But she did not do what she was there for. Also she could not life her legs to get helped to get dressed to come to the hospital. Now patient is able to shuffle to the toilet. Now she is able to answer her name and birthday. But still patient looks confused and not her baseline. Patient has difficulty remembering her medications. Patient does remember her children's name and home address. Patient lives alone at home and daughter wishes patient to be monitored as she has not recovered completely.  Hospital Course/Treatment Rendered 78/F, CC : altered mental status PMHx Endometrioid adenocarcinoma stage IA, grade 2, status post hysterectomy and BSO on 04/06/2015. Diabetes type 2. HTN. HLD. Altered mental status, Encephalopathy, metabolic, likely related to COVID 19 vaccination. Neuro status as well as hemodynamics been monitored. Fall precaution. PT/OT was consulted for home safety evaluation as patient lives alone. Neurology, Dr. was consulted. Patient refused lumber puncture in ED. CT chest - no pneumonia or Pulmonary embolism. UA - ketone positive and dehydrated but no UTI. In the morning of 3/14/2021, patient has improved and mental status back to baseline. PT deemed patient able to go home safe. Uncontrolled hypertension at ED. Gentle hydration as patient has dehydration(urine specific gravity 1.026) and continue antihypertensives such as losartan. SBP 145-165mmHg, Asymptomatic. Will continue home medication. High D-dimer. CTA chest - excluded DVT. Venous duplex US of Both Lower extremity in AM done and no evidence of DVT. Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus. continue to monitor blood glucose and continue glipizide. controlled with blood glucose 188-135.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Vaccine administration error. The vaccine was given to a 16yr old. Licensed for 18 years +.

Within the first 24 hours she showed a look of serious aging, and then the following day extreme pain in the mid and left side back making it difficult to walk or move. Severe pain. The pain seem to shift around like more nerve pain showing in the muscle . Started on the left side but moved around.  This was initially helped with some strong curcummin/boswella (inflammation pain formula at our health food store) and a homeopathic remedy. But the symptoms came back and kept going . She is very active and was unable to do her regular routine. She was sleeping more and in considerable pain. After several days, we tried what another country recommends for reactions to vaccines and it seemed to help her within a very short time. There is still now residual pain but she is better.  We have GREAT concern over what a second dose could do and do not feel that with such a strong reaction the second dose safe. Also a great concern that the same amount of vaccine for a 250 pound person and a 100 pound elder. She is very tiny bones and weighs around 100 pounds are less. Very concerning as no medicine is usually the same for everyone. Also a concern of why just one month from second dose when it takes a known 6 weeks for blood to change. A high chance of severe reaction can happen with such a close proximity and a second dose. We would like to see advise of no second shot or considerable less for small people. CDC person recommended she switch vaccines?  That seems risky and there is no studies of adverse reaction to combining two different vaccines.  She would like to be comfortable moving around in public and is of great health for her age so this reaction was very concerning. If she had such a reaction on FIRST DOSE....wouldnt that be a indication that her body reacted and a second dose not necessary  advisable. Please advise. This is of great concern to all of us who love her and of great concern for the general public who may be at risk for such adverse effects. I put unknown below because she still feels some pain even though it is less.
HISTORY: none super healthy/   I am naturally healthy.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: 1/23/2021 - The first Moderna vaccine. I had flu like symptoms, which included fatigue, muscles aches, muscle spasms, joint aches, chills, and shortness of breath for 2-3 days afterward.  2/20/2021 - The second Moderna vaccine. The side effects were much worse, including muscle aches, abdominal pain, back pain, headache, nausea, chills,  fatigue, and shortness of breath. I also found myself limping. 2/21, 2/22, 2/23 - I rested and stayed home from work. Most of my symptoms had improved by the evening of the 23rd, and I felt like the shortness of breath was also improving if I took it easy.  2/24 - I went to work where the shortness of breath became much worse after working for a couple of hours. I began to get dizzy, and my hands and feet were cold and tingling. The school nurse checked my temperature (which was normal) and oxygen levels (99%). I was sent home and told to take another day or two off.  I was fine if I was sitting still and doing nothing, but talking caused me to become winded. Walking and exertion of any kind caused me to become winded. Once winded, it would take 15 minutes of sitting still to get my breathing back under control. Then I would be hit by a wave of fatigue. Also, when my breathing was bad, I walked with a limp. 2/25 - I went to  the shortness of breath was still bad. They were concerned. They took a chest x-ray (which came back clear), did blood work (which was normal), and gave me a Rapid Covid test (which was negative). My oxygen levels were at 99%. They prescribed a 6 day pack of MethylPREDNISolon. If I was not better by Saturday, they wanted me to return. They also did a PCR test (this came back negative on 2/28).  2/26 - The steroid did not help, and by the evening, I was worse.  I went to the ER . The doctors there were concerned about a pulmonary embolism. They did blood work (which was normal), a chest x-ray (which came back clear), and an EKG (which was normal). My vitals were good, though my blood pressure was high for me (113/64). The doctor told me to continue the steroid pack and prescribed an albuterol inhaler. I was directed to contact a pulmonary specialist on 3/1 if symptoms did not improve. The doctor wrote a note for me to work from home through 3/5. 3/1 - The shortness of breath did not improve. I almost passed out while driving after I picked up my two small children from school. I could not catch my breath in the car and started to get lightheaded. When I parked, I stayed in the car huffing and puffing for several minutes. I was seeing spot, was dizzy, and my hands and feet were tingling. When I climbed out of the car, my legs buckled beneath me. I was able to grab onto the car and not fall. I had some really bad breathing episodes between 3/1-and 3/3. At these times, the breathing was so rough, that I couldn?t even talk. It would take 30 minutes or more of sitting still for me to be able to bring my breathing under control. 3/3 - Appointment with Pulmonary Specialist. I had an appointment  He ruled out asthma, as the inhaler and steroid were both ineffective. He considered anxiety, but the problem was clearly not a panic or anxiety attack. (I have experienced those before and know the difference.) He ruled that out. He ran a pulmonary function test (which was normal) and a CT scan with contrast (which was normal). The doctor wrote a note for me to work from home through 3/10.  3/4 and on - My breathing was better some days than others. The less energy I exerted, the better I did. If I did too much one day, my breathing would be worse the next day.  3/7 - Ajovy injection. I was past due for this monthly injection. Once injected, I had an allergic reaction to it for the first time ever (this was the 7th time I used it). A few minutes after the injection, the injection area had a rash and was itching like crazy. I put ice on it and took benadryl. It was fine by the next morning.  3/9 - Appointment #2 with Pulmonary Specialist. The specialist was not sure what the problem was with my breathing. I was the first patient with these vaccine side effects that he had seen. He scheduled more tests and said he wanted to read more literature. He wrote a note for me to work from home through 4/6.
LAB_DATA: 2/25/2021 - Chest x-ray (which came back clear), blood work (which was normal), a Rapid Covid test (which was negative), and a PCR test (this came back negative on 2/28).  2/26 -  Chest x-ray (which came back clear), blood work (which was normal aside from slight anemia), and an EKG (which was normal).  3/3 - Pulmonary function test (which was normal) and a CT scan with contrast (which was normal).

SYMPTOM_TEXT: This is a positive one, and I can hardly believe it. My irregular pupil dilation independent of each other, occuring for 12 years corrected itself! I swear this is not a joke. I'm flabbergasted.   The longer explanation:  Something I never talk about, partially because I am scared, is an issue with my eyes that started when I was 19. I am now 36.  My right pupil will dilate quite irregularly from my left. A bright light will correct it, but then it will start again after. I've mentioned it to eye doctors, and they brushed it off. Research only has scary answers, with no help, so I have learned to live with it.  It used to make me dizzy, nauseous, and I'd lay down. But over the years I've adjusted, and it doesn't bother me.  I received the first dose of the Pfizer vaccine on 3/11. Last night, 3/14, I became dizzy and faint.   Today, I still felt that way. I was splashing cold water on my face, when I realized, looking in the mirror, my pupils were exactly the same size! And maintained that same diameter.  I keep checking, but, so far, it's consistent.   I assume the dizziness, lack of balance, and slight faintness today is my body getting used to this, as it's been compensating for the difference for 12 years.  So, is this a positive side effect? A coincidence? The vaccine is the only recent change, and nothing else has effected this issue over the years.
HISTORY: Irregular pupil dilation of right eye, independent from left.

Cardiology reports shows Troponin was elevated to 9.1 decreased to 4.2 and back up again to 13.4. Cardiac revealed late gadolinium enhancement, possibly representing myocarditis and then at discharge possibly myocarditis.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: He had the injection, had the sore arm and approximately 3 hours after the vaccination he began to experience severe chest pain across his entire chest and into his jaw, which was exacerbated upon taking a deep breath.  He called his cardiologist who advised him to go to the ER.  He was worked up, subsequently admitted from 2/8/21 to 2/11/21, a lot was ruled out but no specific diagnosis made at that time.  They did note some pleural effusion and pericardial effusion at that time.  Upon discharge on 2/11/21, starting Thursday evening he continued to have pain in the chest, but not as severe as when he entered into the hospital.  Every evening including last night has began with severe night sweats, low grade fever and the chest pains have continued.  Went to see his PCP,  Cardiologist and his Electrophysiologist several days later the following after discharge, he does have a pacemaker, and was told by all three of them that he has pericarditis and that the reaction could have been related to the vaccination.  It seemed more than coincidental that the symptoms did not appear until 3 hours after the vaccine.  Was put on Colchicine to treat the pericarditis and then received a 2nd opinion and has reinstituted the colchicine.  His low grade fever has finally dissipated.  During the day he feels okay, but still continues with the chest pains and the night sweats.  His hemoglobin dropped in the hospital possibly related to the heparin and then put on Eliquis postop, and now discontinued, and received an iron infusion to boost his hemoglobin.  He is scheduled for another iron infusion this Wednesday.    He  went to see GI physician and feels that he may have a bleed due to the infusion.   He has had an anastomosis due to Crohn's disease and feels that's where the bleed may have been coming from as he did have an ulceration at last colonoscopy.  He did have atrial flutter due this and was advised to have an ablation, and trying to reduce the pericarditis and FU later with other heart related problems.
LAB_DATA: Low hemoglobin, iron infusion given, scheduled for repeat on Wednesday, last was 8.5.  Did have blood work and C-reactive protein, and all blood work are elevated.
OTHER_MEDS: Flecainide, Metoprolol, Pentasa, Six MP, Lexapro, Welchol, Budesonide, Famotidine, Trazodone, Hematenic/folic acid, Colchicine, Carafate, multivitamin, Vitamin D3, B12 injection.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Received the vaccine on Thursday 3/11 3:15PM.  Around 2PM on Friday 3/12, noticed that my right jaw was feeling sore when I chewed on things.  Didn't think much of it until dinner time when my jaw hurt everytime I took a bite of food.  Couldn't think of anything I did to cause it, and assumed it would get better soon. On Saturday, my jaw was still sore when I had lunch, but maybe a little better.  But then at dinner time it was back to hurting again.  Sunday it was still sore when  I had lunch.  By then I was starting to attribute it to possibly being the vaccine I received on 3/11, even though there was no mention of this as a side effect on any of the sheets I received when I got my vaccine.  I then signed-up to v-safe to see what they might offer. Then I called the on-call nurseline (where I got the shot).  An RN called back and we went over everything, and at the end she recommended I go into an Emergency room to get checked out because jaw paint can possibly mean heart issues or other things to be concerned about.  I was very surprised about her recommendation, but decided to take her advice.  Went to an emergency clinic.   While I was in the waiting room, a woman who was also waiting said she heard me talking about the reason I was in and said her husband had experienced the same symptoms after his Covid vaccine that I did!  He had a Moderna shot on 2/27 and then several days later his right jaw got sore.  He went to the doctor on 3/8 and they said he had TMJ, but the next day his pain went away and he has been ok since.  They examined me, took blood for Troponin, did an EKG.  All looked OK.  I told them about the person in the waiting room and her husband and they said they weren't aware that this was an issue with this vaccine.  They sent me home and said to monitor and follow-up with my family doctor if it persists.  As of today,  I am still having the pain in my right jaw.  It has stayed the same since it started - no better/no worse.  I suspect of there are 2 of us with this symptom, there are probably many others.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had the Pfizer vaccine in my left arm on Jan. 23rd. I had no side effects at the time, other than a sore arm, as with any shot. However, two days later I lost all hearing in my left ear. I had no history of ear infections or other ear or hearing problems, except for wax buildup two or three times. On Jan. 26th, I saw an ENT. To my dismay, there was no wax. He prescribed the standard treatment of Prednisone for Sudden Idiopathic Hearing Loss. No change after the first round, so I had a second round, and also had the series of three ear injections with Dexamethasone. Had an MRI, as well, which was normal. A couple of weeks into all this, I began to have a bit of sound-generated static in my ear, and this continues today. (Fortunately, I?ve only had the most minor of tinnitus in that ear, and even it is pretty much gone now.)

The day I got the vaccine, I waited 15 minutes at the clinic for any immediate adverse reaction.  While driving myself home, I felt this strange sensation of warmth course through my body and immediate light-headedness resulted.  I wondered if I were going to pass out and whether I should pull over.  But I continued driving home and have been light-headed (even dizzy if I move my head too much) since then.  I tried drinking a lot of water, resting, taking an antihistamine and ibuprofen, but none of those changed the way I felt, although it doesn't feel as bad if I am sitting still and lying down.  After six days of no improvement, I went to the doctor (on March 15th), who prescribed meclizine to help with the light-headedness.  They also took blood to check for other possible causes of the light-headedness.  They said the feeling will probably go away, and they gave me a doctor's note indicating that my second does of the vaccine could be Johnson and Johnson, since that is not an mRNA drug .  They said I should wait 28 days at least before getting that.  I will likely wait a little longer than that just to be safe, and I will not even take that if this feeling doesn't go away by then.
LAB_DATA: As mentioned above, so far all they have done is take my blood to test for thyroid function or other things that could make me feel light-headed.
OTHER_MEDS: Regular strength multivitamin; Vitamin D, 2000 IU; Calcium carbonate 750 mg. 3 x day; Metamucil fiber supplement, 1 T. day.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine EUA At ~10 minutes into my 15 minute "observation" period post vaccine, I became extremely dizzy and weak; feeling as if I would fall out of my chair.  I gripped the chair with both hands and put my head down between my knees. 2 EMTs that were on-site came over and talked to me; put me into a wheel chair and took me to their "tent" area in the gym and had me lay down on a cot.  They kept me under observation (completing blood pressure, heart rate, pulse-ox, and temp monitoring) for ~1 hour/15 minutes.  I was somewhat recovered, and wanted to go home. They told me I should contact my doctor for evaluation before returning for the second dose, scheduled for 4 weeks out.   An EMT walked me to my car.  I drove myself home.  I continued to experience continuous (but milder) dizziness and weakness for the rest of the day,  mostly recovered by the following morning. (I also experienced typical side effects of soreness at the injection site, starting later that first day; and mild headache and fatigue the following day).
LAB_DATA: Sat. 3/13/21 (day of injection) - EMT monitoring (see above) all normal. Sun. 3/14/21: Messaged my MD re: the issue to schedule appointment for assessment.  That is pending at this writing.
OTHER_MEDS: calcium, vitamin D, B-complex, vitamin C - dietary supplements
HISTORY: None History Breast Cancer (2007) = 14 years out

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I was told by my doctor after talking with his office on the phone to report my reaction and that he is recommending that I NOT HAVE THE SECOND DOSE of this vaccine.  On Tuesday March 9th I had my first dose of the Pfizer vaccine at our drive up site with the health department. I did not have any tylenol or claritin that morning and only took Tylenol that night. Starting the NIGHT of the 10th I started taking my usual Child's dose of Claritin for seasonal allergies. I took Claritin the nights of the  10th, 11th and 12th (thank goodness apparently). The only issue I had the 9th and 10th was  REALLY SORE ARM.  One the morn ing of Saturday the 13th I woke up and my neck was itching. Then my decollete area. Then my face and head and shoulders and the back of my arms. I felt like I was flushing after a steroid shot with the pin prickly itching and very very very slight pink color to my skin. Eventually by the evening the itch moved to my bra line. I called my local pharmacy (since the urgent care center was closed) and was told to take benedryl or claritin and keep an eye on it. The ADULT dose of Claritin really helped to calm the majority of the itching. I itched a little yesterday and still itch in spots today but the Claritin is helping as is topical Cortaid.  The nurse said the claritin I had in my system probably prevented me from turning red. I have been told by two doctors that I should NOT take the second dose.  ALL OF THE CONVERSATION WITH MY DOCTOR WAS DONE OVER THE PHONE.
OTHER_MEDS: Did not take any children's Claritin the day before or the day of vaccination. I only started taking the children's dose of claritin on the night of the 10th for my seasonal allergies like I usually do.

Everything red started itching was raised like hives.  I found three dots on my arm and later those spread into large spots of hives. I took another 50mg at 10 when I was having no relief and it continued to spread.  At 1:15am both of my hands and wrists had hives and these hurt and itched the most because they were swollen and hard to bend.  At 3am both of my feet started to flair up.  Finally around 5am the hives stopped.  I was not able to sleep through it.  I did not ever have a fever, I checked that 4 times.  I also did not have trouble breathing or have any swelling on my face. 3-15-21 @ 9:20am I went to see my doctor.  All of my vitals were good.  All of my hives were gone.  He put me on Prednisone in case it came back and at 11am I took 4 pills and went to bed.  I woke up 2 hours later and my feet were itching again.  My left foot broke out in hives bad.   It lasted for over an hour.  My toes were hard to bend.   4:34pm on 3-15-21 currently I don't have any hives and I am tired.    I thoroughly thought through everything that I have eaten, worn, and used, and I have changed nothing over the past 2 weeks.

Approx 25 mintues after the vaccine (at 10:55AM), pt c/o itching/burning in the back of right thigh. Checked area, erythema and warmth noted of a 4inch diameter area on posterior right thigh. Also noted urticaria on right dorsal forearm and right inner forearm, each approx 2 inch diameter. Also urticaria noted at base of left thumb at crease of wrist, approx 1 inch diameter. patient c/o itching at all sites. Denies any respiratory sxs, no odd sensation in mouth/throat/tongue/lips. See ROS and PE for further details. Gave pt 25mg oral benadryl capsule with water. She had mild sensation of sleepiness afterward. Within 30 minutes the urticaria on the right forearm was resolved. The left base of thum/wrist area was with mild erythema, The posterior left thigh area was much paler and pt states all areas no longer were itching. VSS, BP was decreaed to WNL.  Additional post-vaccine screening: patient states she feels fine and was ready to go home. She lives at home with her 20 yo son who was going to be home all day today. She plans to go home and relex. Gave pt three more samples of 25mg benadryl and instructed to take at least one more dose today at bedtime, but to take every 6 hours as needed. Also reviewed s/s to take her epipen, and when she should go to ER or call 911. Also instructed pt that she should not receive the second dose of moderna vaccine. Will contact pt tomorrow to check on her. Advised her to notify her PCP of the reaction. Advised she may wish to consult her allergist in future if another covid vaccine may be appropriate. Patient verbalizes understanding and agreement with plan of care. patient d/c home after a full 75 minutes of observation. Will complete the VAERS form
